The paper deals with the problem of identifying sparse linear time-invariant (LTI) systems from a single sample trajectory generated by the system dynamics. This problem is related to system identification, which falls under the category of control theory and systems engineering. Therefore, cs.SY (Systems and Control) is the most likely sub-category. 

The paper also introduces a Lasso-like estimator for the parameters of the system, which takes into account their sparse nature. This involves optimization and statistical learning techniques, which are relevant to machine learning and data science. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a likely sub-category. 

The paper also discusses the sample complexity bounds for the sparse system identification problem, which involves information theory and signal processing. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) are also likely sub-categories. 

Finally, the paper presents a case study on power systems, which involves numerical simulations and optimization techniques. Therefore, cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) is also a likely sub-category.
